Mechanical impulse getting the water to explode (or implode, as in cavitation) - a high-voltage discharge, perhaps concentrated by a magnetron...

Worth consideration and experimentation.

@ghz24 it's not rust that you make (Fe2O3), but magnetic oxide (Fe3O4)
HERE IS THE FORMULA: 3Fe (at 800°c) + 4 H2O (at more than 100°c, in the vapor state) give:
Fe3O4 (magnetic oxide) + 4H2 (4 dihydrogen) + 38,000 cal/g (a heat surplus of 38,000 gram calories)

@ghz24 this is untrue. Plenty of research papers on pulse width modulation used to improve efficiency in electrolysis (minimum effect is surface gas removal on electrodes - "bubble removal and replenishment of ions are the main causes of this improvement, as well as the perturbation of the electrical double layer"). Read the open access journal Electrochimica Acta. It's all laid out in there. 

Pulsed water electrolysis decreases power input while maintaining the current at a minimum level at which gas cross-over is not an issue.

Also another area to research is spark gap electrolysis and cavitation.

@scaloi Good luck. My experimentation with hho on a 2003 diesel hilux didn't produce the results I wanted but it was a thoroughly worthwhile project with regards to learning the finer arts of efficient hydrogen production along with plenty of explosive and interesting ways of experimentation. It taught me even more about human nature. There were a lot of crazy, unrealistic claims from many doing the experiments but also a lot of unimaginative dismissals from folk who tried to frame the problems in simplistic terms.

I tried something that I don't  think anyone else tried with regards to infusing the diesel itself with micro bubbles of browns gas rather than floating it in from the intake manifold. The idea was to impart the properties of the hydrogen and oxygen into the diesel hoping to convert more of the heat energy of the burn into kinetic energy. Effectively hoping to bring the thermal efficiently higher than 30%. The water injection idea as you know is attempting to do the same thing.

I thought the concept was sound but the diesel fuel became extremely explosive once the gas was mixed in it. I then remembered that diesel and nitrogen is used in making explosives for opal mining. I know nitrogen and hydrogen are very different gasses but the results with the hydrogen was way too violent to continue the experiments safely without a much more sophisticated understanding than I had.

